5. ab universis vicis, ‘by villages as communities.' This reading, pre- served in one MS. aud probably indi-

caied by the corruption ‘vices' (for which ‘in vices' and ‘invicem' may be corrections), is adopted by Z.. also by Waitz and other writers, and gives the hest sense to the passage, which appears to describe a free village (as contrasted with that noted in c. 25, 1). The form of such a village community found later in Germany is that called the mark sys- tem, on which see Von Maurer, in Sir H. Maine,Village Communities, pp. 78- 82. The communityas such was pos· · sessed of a tract of land, divided into three marks or portions; (1) the mark of the township or village, the ground aautttlklltlftrtkltn land or pasture mark, held by all in mixed ownership under supervisi0n; (3) the arable mark, taken out of the common for cultivation, divided into three great fields, of which one lay fal· low every year. A portion of this mark was allotted to and cultivated by every family, subject to fixed rnles of cropping and fallowing. We cannot, indeed, re· coguize this system as a whole iu the description here ,given (see following notes), but we have perhaps an account of some state of things out of which it may have grown. Those who bracket ‘vices’ (as Halm), or read ‘in vices’ or ‘invicem ’ (with a reference to ‘arva mutant' below) would still make the land to be occupied ‘ab universis,' i. e. by communities of meu, such as probably clans or great families (see Introd. pp. 22, 32).
